   by any party.

6. NO INTENT TO CAUSE HARM, ECONOMIC LOSS, OR BUSINESS INTERFERENCE
   The Owner's sole and exclusive purpose is personal browsing privacy,
   security, and safety on the Owner's own personal devices. The Owner has
   absolutely no intent, purpose, or objective to:
   (a) cause economic harm, revenue loss, or financial damage to any person,
       company, advertiser, publisher, ad network, ad technology provider,
       data broker, analytics provider, or any other entity;
   (b) interfere with, disrupt, or impede the business operations, business
       relationships, contractual arrangements, or economic interests of any
       entity;
   (c) engage in unfair competition, tortious interference, or any form of
       anti-competitive behavior;
   (d) circumvent, defeat, or undermine any technological protection measures,
       digital rights management systems, or access controls;
   (e) violate or infringe upon any intellectual property rights, contractual
       rights, or proprietary interests of any entity.
   The filter rules contained herein originate entirely from independent,
   publicly available, third-party open-source projects maintained by their
   own communities; the Owner merely aggregates them for personal convenience.

7. RIGHT TO PERSONAL PRIVACY, SECURITY, AND DEVICE AUTONOMY
   The use of content-filtering, ad-blocking, and tracker-blocking tools for
   personal privacy, security, and safety is a well-established, recognized,
   and lawful exercise of an individual's fundamental right to:
   (a) control what content is loaded, rendered, and executed on their own
       personal devices;
   (b) protect their personal data, browsing activity, and digital identity
       from unauthorized collection, tracking, profiling, and surveillance;
   (c) safeguard their devices from malware, phishing, cryptojacking,
       fingerprinting, and other security threats.
   This right is consistent with, and protected by, applicable privacy and
   data protection legislation and fundamental user autonomy principles
   recognized in jurisdictions worldwide, including but not limited to:
   - European Union / EEA: General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR,
     Regulation 2016/679), ePrivacy Directive (2002/58/EC)
   - India: Information Technology Act, 2000; Digital Personal Data
     Protection Act, 2023 (DPDPA)
   - United States: California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA/CPRA), state
     privacy laws, First Amendment protections
   - Canada: Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act
     (PIPEDA), provincial privacy statutes
   - United Kingdom: UK GDPR, Data Protection Act 2018
   - Switzerland: Federal Act on Data Protection (FADP/nDSG, revised 2023)
   - United Arab Emirates: Federal Decree-Law No. 45 of 2021 on Personal
     Data Protection
   - People's Republic of China: Personal Information Protection Law (PIPL),
     Cybersecurity Law, Data Security Law
   - Australia: Privacy Act 1988 (Cth), Australian Privacy Principles
   - Japan: Act on Protection of Personal Information (APPI)
   - South Korea: Personal Information Protection Act (PIPA)
   - Singapore: Personal Data Protection Act 2012 (PDPA)
   - Brazil: Lei Geral de Protecao de Dados (LGPD, Law No. 13,709/2018)
   - South Africa: Protection of Personal Information Act (POPIA)
   - All other jurisdictions with applicable privacy, data protection, or
     consumer protection legislation
   Legal precedent in multiple jurisdictions (including the Hamburg Regional
   Court ruling in Axel Springer SE v. Eyeo GmbH and subsequent German
   Federal Court of Justice decisions) has established that the use and
   distribution of ad-blocking software does not constitute unfair competition
   or tortious interference with business.

8. AD REVENUE AND PUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPS
   The Owner acknowledges that online advertising is a legitimate business
   model. However, the Owner's personal choice to filter content on the
   Owner's own devices does not constitute:
   (a) interference with any contractual relationship between advertisers and
       publishers, as the Owner is not a party to any such contract;
   (b) unfair business practice, as the Owner derives no commercial benefit;
   (c) circumvention of access controls, as the filter operates entirely on
       the client side of the Owner's own device and does not modify, hack,
       or interfere with any server, service, website, or network;
   (d) any form of copyright infringement, as filtering content on receipt
       does not reproduce, distribute, or create derivative works of any
       copyrighted material.
   The Owner does not block any specific advertiser or publisher with targeted
   intent — the aggregated filter rules are community-maintained lists that
   operate based on general pattern matching.

